1
00:00:01,485 --> 00:00:08,330
[SPEAKER_13]: All right, this is the Medford Historical Commission meeting for October 16th, 2023.

2
00:00:08,371 --> 00:00:10,732
[SPEAKER_13]: I'll call the meeting to order at 7.03 p.m.

3
00:00:10,752 --> 00:00:13,455
[SPEAKER_13]: I'll begin by reading the governor's blurb.

4
00:00:13,995 --> 00:00:25,584
[SPEAKER_13]: On March 29th, 2023, Governor Healey signed into law a supplemental budget bill, which among other things, extends the temporary provisions pertaining to the open meeting law to March 31st, 2025,

5
00:00:27,746 --> 00:00:41,149
[SPEAKER_13]: Specifically, this further extension allows public bodies to continue holding meetings remotely without a quorum of the public body physically present at a meeting location and to provide adequate alternative access to remote meetings.

6
00:00:41,590 --> 00:00:51,352
[SPEAKER_13]: The language does not make any substantive changes to the open meeting law other than extending the expiration date of the temporary provisions regarding the remote meetings from March 31st, 2023 to March 31st, 2025.

7
00:00:57,868 --> 00:01:01,231
[SPEAKER_13]: Okay, we have up on the agenda tonight.

8
00:01:03,093 --> 00:01:04,894
[SPEAKER_13]: First up, 56 Wareham Street.

9
00:01:05,015 --> 00:01:11,200
[SPEAKER_13]: Is there anybody here from 56 Wareham Street to drop off application?

10
00:01:11,220 --> 00:01:14,844
[SPEAKER_13]: All right, hearing none, we'll table that.

11
00:01:16,205 --> 00:01:21,370
[SPEAKER_13]: If we receive, I'm gonna remove it from the agenda, and if we receive the information, we'll act on it accordingly.

12
00:01:23,258 --> 00:01:38,043
[SPEAKER_13]: For the next three items, 69 Court Street, 587 Winthrop Street, and 64 Myrtle Street will be receiving the demolition applications and then moving right to a determination of significance.

13
00:01:38,623 --> 00:01:46,006
[SPEAKER_13]: In the case of that, the historical commission is determining whether or not a building is

14
00:01:46,746 --> 00:02:03,804
[SPEAKER_13]: either been listed on the National Register of Historic Places or has been listed on the Massachusetts Register of Historic Places or was built 75 years or older determined by the commission to be significant either because it is importantly associated with one or more historic

15
00:02:04,244 --> 00:02:22,590
[SPEAKER_13]: or events, or with a broad architectural, cultural, political, economic, or social history of the city or the Commonwealth, or it is historically or architecturally important in terms of period style, method of building construction, or association with an important architect or builder, either by itself or in the context of a group of buildings.

16
00:02:23,771 --> 00:02:26,412
[SPEAKER_13]: So the way these meetings work is that we will

17
00:02:28,252 --> 00:02:31,835
[SPEAKER_13]: We had the MHC form Bs prepared for each one of these structures.

18
00:02:32,175 --> 00:02:40,160
[SPEAKER_13]: They're available on our website at medfordhistoricalcommission.org, and you can go on our blog and follow along.

19
00:02:40,921 --> 00:02:43,483
[SPEAKER_13]: We use the MHC forms to make our determinations.

20
00:02:43,903 --> 00:02:45,444
[SPEAKER_13]: We'll have commissioner comments.

21
00:02:45,464 --> 00:02:48,886
[SPEAKER_13]: If there's any comments from the applicants, have those afterwards.

22
00:02:49,267 --> 00:02:56,852
[SPEAKER_13]: We'll wrap up with finalizing any motions, and then we'll move forward accordingly based on how those motions pass.

23
00:02:58,931 --> 00:03:03,697
[SPEAKER_13]: So the first item up on the agenda tonight is 6769 Court Street.

24
00:03:04,037 --> 00:03:08,062
[SPEAKER_13]: Commissioners, I sent around the demolition application.

25
00:03:09,163 --> 00:03:17,414
[SPEAKER_13]: If that application is in order, we can take that application as complete and move right to the termination of significance for both the house and carriage house.

26
00:03:21,241 --> 00:03:23,422
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, so we're making two separate determinations.

27
00:03:23,923 --> 00:03:31,587
[SPEAKER_13]: Yeah, you would first accept the application and once the application is determined, complete and accepted, then we can move right into the termination of significance.

28
00:03:33,568 --> 00:03:39,491
[SPEAKER_08]: Motion to accept the application for the house and the carriage house for 6769 Court Street.

29
00:03:41,052 --> 00:03:41,472
[SPEAKER_04]: Second.

30
00:03:42,553 --> 00:03:43,733
[SPEAKER_13]: Peter Miller, second.

31
00:03:45,534 --> 00:03:47,916
[SPEAKER_13]: Okay, go around the room, roll call vote.

32
00:03:48,676 --> 00:03:49,737
[SPEAKER_13]: As I see you, Peter.

33
00:03:50,599 --> 00:03:50,879
[SPEAKER_12]: Yes.

34
00:03:51,719 --> 00:03:51,999
[SPEAKER_13]: Jen?

35
00:03:52,679 --> 00:03:53,079
[SPEAKER_12]: Yes.

36
00:03:53,580 --> 00:03:53,860
[SPEAKER_12]: Jess?

37
00:03:54,540 --> 00:03:54,860
[SPEAKER_12]: Yes.

38
00:03:55,940 --> 00:03:56,380
[SPEAKER_12]: And Doug?

39
00:03:57,320 --> 00:03:57,600
[SPEAKER_12]: Yes.

40
00:03:58,240 --> 00:03:58,620
[SPEAKER_13]: Okay, great.

41
00:03:58,880 --> 00:03:59,701
[SPEAKER_13]: Motion passes 4-0.

42
00:04:00,221 --> 00:04:07,642
[SPEAKER_13]: So I need a motion one way or the other to kickstart the discussion for determination of significance.

43
00:04:18,364 --> 00:04:18,664
[SPEAKER_12]: Anybody?

44
00:04:19,466 --> 00:04:20,486
[SPEAKER_12]: I can't make it on the chair.

45
00:04:20,506 --> 00:04:31,910
[SPEAKER_08]: I will motion to find we're going to do them one at a time or no we'll take them together.

46
00:04:33,251 --> 00:04:37,272
[SPEAKER_13]: It's a complete it's a complete demolition package so we'll just take them together.

47
00:04:38,713 --> 00:04:43,094
[SPEAKER_08]: I'll make a motion to find no actually I'm going to refrain.

48
00:04:43,555 --> 00:04:44,755
[SPEAKER_08]: Sorry, that's okay.

49
00:04:49,895 --> 00:04:51,835
[SPEAKER_12]: Doug, Peter, Jess, anything to get it on the table?

50
00:04:51,855 --> 00:04:56,936
[SPEAKER_04]: Go ahead, Peter.

51
00:04:56,996 --> 00:05:01,357
[SPEAKER_13]: I can move to make a motion to find 67 to 69 Court Street significant

52
00:05:20,875 --> 00:05:21,696
[SPEAKER_11]: Okay, thank you.

53
00:05:22,717 --> 00:05:23,378
[SPEAKER_13]: Our second.

54
00:05:25,460 --> 00:05:25,860
[SPEAKER_13]: Okay, great.

55
00:05:26,901 --> 00:05:28,183
[SPEAKER_13]: Motion's been made and seconded.

56
00:05:28,743 --> 00:05:30,125
[SPEAKER_13]: Peter, do you want to kickstart discussion?

57
00:05:35,731 --> 00:05:38,854
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, I'm on the fence about this one.

58
00:05:41,121 --> 00:05:51,329
[SPEAKER_04]: I was gonna qualify my motion to say that I'm probably not gonna find it significant myself, but this gets too wordy.

59
00:05:56,033 --> 00:06:07,121
[SPEAKER_04]: I think this house has been altered a lot, and I don't feel like it rises to the level of being historically significant.

60
00:06:10,314 --> 00:06:11,955
[SPEAKER_04]: That's really how I feel about it.

61
00:06:11,975 --> 00:06:14,895
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

62
00:06:16,336 --> 00:06:18,737
[SPEAKER_03]: Doug?

63
00:06:19,017 --> 00:06:35,862
[SPEAKER_03]: To me, this is actually a little bit more of a close call because I do feel that the additions over the last 50 years have made the house more interesting, telling a longer story than just the original house did.

64
00:06:37,448 --> 00:06:40,710
[SPEAKER_03]: unique additions in the back, especially when you look at the photos of the back of the building.

65
00:06:40,750 --> 00:06:49,615
[SPEAKER_03]: I think there's some really interesting things going on there that I don't think I see in most typical houses.

66
00:06:50,056 --> 00:06:59,481
[SPEAKER_03]: The additions are dwarfed the original house by quite a bit, and they're, I guess, unique architectural features with the curved base and the strange root shapes.

67
00:07:00,202 --> 00:07:05,145
[SPEAKER_03]: It's just really a composite that I think is worth just taking a little closer look at.

68
00:07:08,038 --> 00:07:10,640
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm not sure if that's the right way to put it.

