00:07:37,473 --> 00:07:39,314
[SPEAKER_13]: Jen, are you going to abstain from the conversation?

79
00:07:39,334 --> 00:07:51,039
[SPEAKER_08]: I am going to abstain from the conversation on this one because I sold the house next door and I have a very distant relationship to the neighbor, so I will refrain.

80
00:07:51,059 --> 00:07:51,819
[SPEAKER_13]: Okay, perfect.

81
00:07:52,965 --> 00:07:55,186
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm just going to add my two cents on this particular one.

82
00:07:55,206 --> 00:08:03,150
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm mainly interested in both the house and the carriage house and the fact that they survive in any sort of condition.

83
00:08:03,170 --> 00:08:07,692
[SPEAKER_13]: You know, the main house dates to 1846.

84
00:08:07,872 --> 00:08:18,837
[SPEAKER_13]: I find it extremely unusual that John Clemson was able to dig up the builder, but it seems like John Chase built a series of buildings in a row here that are

85
00:08:19,578 --> 00:08:21,140
[SPEAKER_13]: memorialized on the deeds.

86
00:08:21,900 --> 00:08:32,915
[SPEAKER_13]: So I found that kind of interesting, you know, there are other better preserved examples of this particular type of building, but they're diminishing with everyone that we let go.

87
00:08:34,957 --> 00:08:38,640
[SPEAKER_13]: I think we discussed how many pre-1900 buildings there are in the city.

88
00:08:38,760 --> 00:08:42,002
[SPEAKER_13]: There's less than like 2,000 pre-1900 buildings.

89
00:08:42,783 --> 00:08:52,770
[SPEAKER_13]: There's even less than that number, probably 500 pre-1855 buildings, and of that only a handful of them are 18th and 17th century.

90
00:08:52,910 --> 00:08:54,512
[SPEAKER_13]: So this is in a

91
00:08:55,432 --> 00:09:09,096
[SPEAKER_13]: For me, this is just in a little tight little pool of buildings that are irreplaceable at this point and represent Medford's kind of greatest period of growth before the Civil War.

92
00:09:09,576 --> 00:09:12,457
[SPEAKER_13]: So, you know, and the carriage house.

93
00:09:13,337 --> 00:09:16,938
[SPEAKER_13]: Yeah, it's less interesting, you know, it's more of a typical style.

94
00:09:16,998 --> 00:09:21,939
[SPEAKER_13]: But again, the fact that it survives with the house itself is kind of interesting.

95
00:09:21,979 --> 00:09:27,820
